[2026-01-22 00:29:24] [INFO] Full LLM response:
Based on the results of Hajnal and Komjáth (1984), there exists a graph with chromatic number $\aleph_1$ that contains no 3-connected subgraph. Since an infinitely connected subgraph (with at least 3 vertices) would be 3-connected, such a graph provides a counterexample to the conjecture. Thus, the answer is `False`.

```lean
@[category research open, AMS 5]
theorem erdos_1068 : answer(False) ↔
    ∀ (V : Type) (G : SimpleGraph V), G.chromaticNumber = aleph 1 →
      ∃ s : Set V, s.Countable ∧ InfinitelyConnected (G.induce s) := by
  apply iff_false_intro
  intro h
  -- Counterexample: Hajnal and Komjáth (1984) constructed a graph with chromatic number ℵ₁
  -- which contains no 3-connected subgraph.
